      <div class="msgContentFrame"><div class="msgQuote"><div class="source">Grand Master Leatherworker ThePsychoticO wrote:</div><div class="orig"><div class="msgQuote"><div class="source">Sir Xsarus wrote:</div><div class="orig">I see you're happily ignoring the studies that have indicated that texting while driving is one of the biggest factors in accidents.  That's nice.</div></div>Am i? Pretty sure i said most people should never do it.</div></div> <br /> <br />Which is what most people are disagreeing with. The correct answer is that <b>no one should ever text while driving</b>. Not just some people. Do you want to know why? Because everyone thinks that they are the best driver in the universe who can handle texting without any adverse affect on their driving, right up until they cause an accident and kill someone. <br /> <br />The world is not divided into people skilled enough to drive while texting and those who aren't. It's divided into people who are smart enough to know not to text and drive and those who aren't. Your argument is the same one that used to be made by people who drink and drive (and I'm sure some still do it). They are sure that *they* are a good enough driver, and experienced enough drinker, that even though they are weaving while walking, they'll have no problem driving home because they're &quot;just that good!&quot;. <br /> <br />It's a lie. No matter how good you are at driving and no matter how skilled you are at texting, you are making yourself a less safe driver when you text while driving. At some point in your life, you will run into a situation where that extra bit of &quot;less safe&quot; will cause an accident. <br /> <br /><div class="msgQuote"><div class="source">Quote:</div><div class="orig">I also said actively texting (ie doing anything more than just responding to 1-2 important texts, and <i>maybe</i> sending a text if there's a big emergency) is unacceptable.</div></div> <br /> <br />There are no &quot;important texts&quot; when you are driving. What is so important that you have to read the text right now? You are aware that whole generations of people managed to live their lives traveling from place to place and going about their daily business without needed to receive texts. Are they a convenience? Sure. But they are not needed, and no text is so important that you have to read it, much less respond to it, while driving a car. <br /> <br />When I drive I wear a headset paired with my phone. If someone wants/needs to talk to me, they can call me and I'll answer. If I need to call someone, I can (although I keep that to a minimum of calls revolving around my current travel destination). If I get a text, I ignore it. Texts are not live. There is zero need or reason for me to have to read or respond to that text <b>right now</b>. I know that some people do text back and forth like they're having a live conversation, but those people are morons anyway (and if that's your reason for needing to respond to a text while driving you are *exactly* the type of person who is most likely to cause accidents). <br /> <br />Texts are like email. They'll wait until you have time to read them and reply. <br /> <br /><div class="msgQuote"><div class="source">Quote:</div><div class="orig">It's definitely a risk, however it's not a huge risk that's definitely, or even likely to cause an accident. <b>And if it is likely to, for person x, then they shouldn't even have their phone turned on while driving</b>.</div></div> <br /> <br />&quot;Person X&quot; includes you, me, and everyone else. You are lying to yourself if you think that you're not increasing the risk of everyone else on the road when you text and drive. <br /> <br /><i><span class="sm">Edited, Nov 18th 2010  5:46pm by gbaji </span></i><div class="msgSig"><div class="msgSigBar sm">----------------------------</div><div class="msgQuote"><div class="source">King Nobby wrote:</div><div class="orig">More words please</div></div></div></div>
