      <div class="msgContentFrame"><div class="msgQuote"><div class="source">Belkira the Tulip wrote:</div><div class="orig">For the record, I've never gotten an emergency text. While driving or otherwise. </div></div> <br /> <br />Also, how does one know that a text is an &quot;emergency&quot;? Wouldn't you have to read every single one in order to make sure you didn't miss the one that was super important? Seems like there's a flaw in there somewhere... <br /> <br />When I'm on call, and I have 15 minutes to respond to a page or it'll get escalated and I'll have to explain why I didn't respond in time, and I'm driving and my phone buzzes with a text message I still don't read it until I get where I'm going. If where I'm going is too far to get there in a reasonable amount of time, I'll pull over and respond. I can't possibly read the text, make the decisions I need to make, and call the person I need to call while barreling down the highway anyway, so there isn't a whole lot of point in reading it anyway. Not to mention that aside from hand holding, what I do when on call involves a bit more complex interface than that I've got on my phone anyway. <br /> <br /> <br />I simply cannot understand what anyone could possibly think was so important that they'd need to read a text while driving. And if your judgment is so poor that you actually think that text is important, then your judgment is certainly going to be wrong about your ability to drive while texting.<div class="msgSig"><div class="msgSigBar sm">----------------------------</div><div class="msgQuote"><div class="source">King Nobby wrote:</div><div class="orig">More words please</div></div></div></div>
